<DOC><DOCNO> AP890928-0091 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1244EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-SouthKorea     09-28 0199</FIRST><SECOND>AM-South Korea,0204</SECOND><HEAD>Death Sentences Asked for Radical Students</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Prosecutors Thursday demanded deathsentences for three radical students on trial for the deaths ofseven riot police killed during an anti-government demonstration.   Six other students charged in the case should receive life inprison, the prosecution said in the trial at Pusan DistrictCriminal Court in the southern port city of Pusan.   The proceedings were briefly disrupted when tear gas wasscattered in the court.   The defendants are charged in the fiery deaths of seven riotpolice who stormed the library at Dongui University on May 3 to tryto free five policemen held hostage by radical students.   Students set a library hall on fire, leaving the seven policeofficers in a fire trap. The five hostages were freed.   So far, 71 Dongui students have been indicted on various chargesin connection with the incident, which resulted in a policecrackdown on campus protests and the arrests of hundreds of radicalstudents.   Radical students are a small but vocal minority in South Korea.Their demands include the withdrawal of the 43,000 U.S. troops inSouth Korea and reunification of North and South Korea.</TEXT></DOC>